itary competition, which creates incentives much more powerful than economic self-interest in motivating political reform. A second driver of change was rooted in the social mobilization brought about by industrialization. Economic growth generates new social groups, which over time organize themselves for collective action and seek to participate in the political system. This process does not always lead to the creation of modern states, but under the right circumstances it can and has.<br/>   t///  <br/> ///h[_Q]<br>But how did Denmark moved to the modern state, what and when was the drive of the military competition IN DENMARK, what and when was the drive of social mobilization IN DENMARK; these are not articulated by the author; therefore his argument and the example of DENMARK are disconnected to each other.h///"}]},{"idx":"01f170c8-55d3-4369-8c25-ee34c7ff199b","name":"POLITICAL DECAY","children":[{"idx":"445418fa-31df-4056-81e3-417e3de69081","name":"Institutions decay due to an inherent conservatism to human behavior","NodeDescription":"///t <br/>  Following Samuel Huntington’s definition, political institutions develop by becoming more complex, adaptable, autonomous, and coherent.5 But he argues that they can also decay. Institutions are created to meet certain needs of societies, such as making war, dealing with economic conflicts, and regulating social behavior. But as recurring patterns of behavior, they can also grow rigid and fail to adapt when the circumstances that brought them into being in the first place themselves change. There is an inherent conservatism to human behavior that tends to invest institutions with emotional significance once they are put in place. Anyone who suggests abolishing the British Monarchy, or the American Constitution, or the Japanese emperor and replacing it with something newer and better, faces a huge uphill struggle.<br/>   t///  <br/> ///h  <br/> h///"},{"idx":"0cc10875-553d-4f55-b4d4-640e356cd939","name":"Fall back on 